Below is a systematic breakdown of how the target model is built and which dictionary blocks (in their given orientations) are used:

1)  Analysis of the Main Target Image

   • Total Blocks and Layers  
     – There are six total blocks.  
       1 × red arch at the center base  
       2 × orange cylinders on either side at the base  
       1 × green rectangular block above the arch  
       1 × blue cube above the green block  
       1 × orange wedge‐shaped “roof” on top  

     – Layering from bottom to top:  
       (a) Layer 1 (Base): red arch + two orange cylinders  
       (b) Layer 2: green rectangular block (sitting on top of the arch)  
       (c) Layer 3: blue cube (sitting on the green block)  
       (d) Layer 4: orange wedge block (at the very top, forming the roof)  

   • Spatial Arrangement  
     – The red arch is centered at the bottom with an arched opening facing forward.  
     – One orange cylinder stands on each side (left and right) of the arch.  
     – The green rectangular block spans horizontally across the top of the arch.  
     – A single blue cube is stacked directly on the green block.  
     – Finally, the orange wedge roof sits atop the blue cube, with its ridge running left–right.  

2)  Selecting Exact Block Indices from the Dictionary

   Matching each visible piece in both shape and orientation (no re‐rotation allowed):  
   • Red Arch → Block #1  
   • Orange Cylinders (vertical) → Block #11 (twice)  
   • Green Rectangular Block (horizontal orientation) → Block #9  
   • Blue Cube → Block #6  
   • Orange Roof Wedge (ridge left–right) → Block #15  

   Hence the needed indices are: 1, 11, 11, 9, 6, and 15.  

3)  Assembly Order

Use the following step‐by‐step format (from bottom blocks to top):

{
  Step1: Move block with index 1
  Step2: Move block with index 11
  Step3: Move block with index 11
  Step4: Move block with index 9
  Step5: Move block with index 6
  Step6: Move block with index 15
}
